 28:  Prevention of Future Deaths report Michael Brendan O \u2019 SULLIVAN (died 24.09.13) |url=https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/OSullivan-2014-0012.pdf |website=www.judiciary.uk |publisher=Judiciary.UK |accessdate=26 December 2018 |date=13 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"DWPCoronerReportESA\">{{cite web |title=Department for Work and Pensions Response to Regulation 28 Prevention of Future Deaths Report on Michael Brenden O'Sullivan |url=https://www.judiciary.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/2014-0012-Response-by-DWP.pdf |website=www.judiciary.uk |publisher=Judiciary.UK |accessdate=26 December 2018 |format=PDF |date=2014}}</ref><ref name=\"BarrEtAlESA\">{{cite journal |last1=Barr |first1=B |last2=Taylor-Robinson |first2=D |last3=Stuckler |first3=D |last4=Loopstra |first4=R |last5=Reeves |first5=A |last6=Whitehead |first6=M |title=\u2018First, do no harm\u2019: are disability assessments associated with adverse trends in mental health? A longitudinal ecological study |journal=Journal of Epidemiology and Community Health |date=April 2016 |volume=70 |issue=4 |pages=339\u2013345 |doi=10.1136/jech-2015-206209 |url=https://jech.bmj.com/content/70/4/339 |accessdate=26 December 2018|pmc=4819657 |pmid=26573235 }}</ref><ref name=\"PringESA\">{{cite news |last1=Pring |first1=John |title=Government\u2019s suicide prevention boss refuses to call for action on ESA risk stats |url=https://www.disabilitynewsservice.com/governments-suicide-prevention-boss-refuses-to-call-for-action-on-esa-risk-stats/ |accessdate=26 December 2018 |work=Disability News Service |publisher=Disability News Service |date=8 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/223050/incap_decd_recips_0712.pdf |title=Incapacity Benefit: Deaths of Recipients |publisher=Department of Work and Pensions, UK Government |date=9 July 2012 |accessdate=12 April 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"AshworthHayesESA\">{{cite web |last1=Ashworth-Hayes |first1=Sam |title=Reporting on \"fit for work\" deaths isn't fit for purpose |url=https://fullfact.org/economy/reporting-fit-work-deaths-isnt-fit-purpose/ |website=Full Fact |publisher=Full Fact |accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=TelegraphMortalityESA>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/tomchiversscience/100279306/the-10600-people-died-within-six-weeks-of-being-declared-fit-to-work-by-atos-stat-is-simply-wrong/ | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=The '10,600 people died within six weeks of being declared fit to work by Atos' stat is simply wrong | date=9 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"FOIAESA\">{{cite web |title=Freedom of Information Act 2000 (FOIA) Decision notice |url=https://ico.org.uk/media/action-weve-taken/decision-notices/2015/1431907/fs_50558122.pdf |website=ico.org.uk |publisher=Information Commissioner's Office |accessdate=26 December 2018 |date=8 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BBCDeathDataESA\">{{cite news |title=Benefit claimant death data released |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-34074557 |accessdate=26 December 2018 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=27 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Butler2ESA\">{{cite news |last1=Butler |first1=Patrick |title=Thousands have died after being found fit for work, DWP figures show |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/aug/27/thousands-died-after-fit-for-work-assessment-dwp-figures |accessdate=26 December 2018 |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |date=27 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"GuardianEditorialESA\">{{cite news |title=The Guardian view on welfare reform: death and the benefit system {{!}} Editorial |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/aug/28/the-guardian-view-on-welfare-reform-death-and-the-benefit-system |accessdate=26 December 2018 |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |date=28 August 2015}}</ref> A United Nations report has been written, which is highly critical of Employment Support Allowance.<ref name=\"auto12\">{{cite web|title=Committee on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities|publisher=United Nations|date=November 2016|url=http://www.ohchr.org/EN/HRBodies/CRPD/Pages/InquiryProcedure.aspx?platform=hootsuite}}</ref><ref name=\"GovReportESA\">{{cite web |title=The United Kingdom Government Response to the Report by the United Nations Committee on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities under article 6 of the Optional Protocol to the Convention |url=http://www.ohchr.org/Documents/HRBodies/CRPD/CRPD.C.17.R.3-ENG.doc |accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See Also==\n* [[Work Capability Assessment]]\n* [[Criticism of the Work Capability Assessment]]\n* [[Disability pension]]\n* [[Social Security Disability Insurance]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{UK benefits}}\n\n[[Category:Social security in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Disability in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Welfare state in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "'''Employment and Support Allowance''' ('''ESA''') is a United Kingdom welfare payment for adults younger than the State Pension age who are having difficulty finding work because of their long-term medical condition or a disability. It is a basic income-replacement benefit paid in lieu of wages. It is currently being phased out and replaced with [[Universal Credit]].\n\n==Eligibility for ESA==\nAn individual can put in a claim for ESA if they satisfy all of these conditions:<ref name=\"GovESAEligibility\">{{cite web |title=Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) |url=https://www.gov.uk/employment-support-allowance/eligibility |website=GOV.UK |publisher=Government Digital Service |accessdate=2 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* They live in the United Kingdom\n* They are over the age of sixteen\n* They have not reached their State Pension age\n* They have a sick-note from their doctor\n\nThey will not be paid ESA if they are entitled to [[Statutory sick pay|Statutory Sick Pay]] (which is paid out by a current employer) and it is not possible to receive ESA at the same time as the other main out-of-work benefits, i.e. [[Jobseekers Allowance]] or [[Income Support]]. \n\n[[Universal Credit]], which is received by one million people nationally, can contain a component analogous to ESA.\n\n==The scale of the allowance==\nNo money is paid for the first week. After that, the basic allowance is paid to the claimant until their [[Work Capability Assessment]] (WCA) at - in theory - week 13, after which a successful claimant might receive an enhanced level of payment (depending on the level of disability and whether they enter the work-related activity group or the support group after their assessment).<ref name=\"ESARates\">{{cite web|title=ESA: what you'll get|publisher=gov.uk|url=https://www.gov.uk/employment-support-allowance/what-youll-get|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202223227/https://www.gov.uk/employment-support-allowance/what-youll-get|archivedate=2016-02-02}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|'''<u><big>ESA Rates for 2019/2020</big></u>'''\n|\n|\n|-\n| ||paid in weeks 2\u201313 <br>\n| paid from week 14\n\n|-\n|Basic allowance (for those aged under 25)\n|\u00a357.90 Per week ||\u00a357.90 Per week\n|-\n|Basic allowance (for those aged 25 and over)\n|\u00a373.10 Per week||\u00a373.10 Per week\n|-\n|Work-related activity component (no longer paid to new claimants)* \n| \u2014\u2014\u2014 ||\u00a329.05 Per week\n|-\n|Support component*\n| \u2014\u2014\u2014 || \u00a338.55 Per week\n|}\n\n<nowiki>* Only one of these components is payable per claim\n</nowiki>\n\nIn April 2017, the work-related activity component was abolished for new claimants. The same applies to successful reclaims, if more than a certain time has elapsed since the last period of receipt of ESA (long-term successful claimants who had a WCA before April 2017 continue to receive it). People receiving the support component are unaffected.\n\nAn enhanced disability premium of \u00a316.80 a week may be paid to single people receiving the support component of income-related ESA; for a couple, the rate is \u00a324.10 where one or both partners qualify.\n\nIn some circumstances, an additional severe disability premium of \u00a365.85 a week may be paid.<ref name=\"ESARates\"/>\n\n==Types of ESA==\nESA can be either contributory or income-related.\n===Contributory and Income-Related ESA===\nIf claimants have paid enough [[National Insurance]] they can claim contributory ESA. Income-related ESA is for people who have not paid enough National Insurance contributions and is subject to a [[means test]] and certain other conditions (although the amount paid as contributions-based ESA can also be affected by financial circumstances). A person must have [[Capital rule|capital]] of less than \u00a316,000 to be eligible for income-based ESA. This includes any savings that the claimant or their spouse or partner may own.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/employment-support-allowance/overview |title=Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) |publisher=GOV.UK |date=2015-08-24 |accessdate=2015-08-30 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906030426/https://www.gov.uk/employment-support-allowance/overview |archivedate=2015-09-06 }}</ref> Income-related ESA is not time-limited<ref name=CAB>{{cite web|title=Employment and Support Allowance|url=http://www.adviceguide.org.uk/england/benefits_e/benefits_sick_or_disabled_people_and_carers_ew/employment_and_support_allowance.htm|publisher=Citizens Advice Bureau|accessdate=27 February 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140312160318/http://www.adviceguide.org.uk/england/benefits_e/benefits_sick_or_disabled_people_and_carers_ew/employment_and_support_allowance.htm|archivedate=12 March 2014}}</ref> and is not usually subject to Income Tax, but contribution-based ESA is.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ageuk.org.uk/money-matters/claiming-benefits/employment-support-allowance/what-is-employment-and-support-allowance/ |title=What is Employment and Support Allowance &#124; Claiming benefits &#124; Money matters |publisher=Age UK |date=2015-05-22 |accessdate=2015-08-30 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915073036/http://www.ageuk.org.uk/money-matters/claiming-benefits/employment-support-allowance/what-is-employment-and-support-allowance/ |archivedate=2015-09-15 }}</ref>\n\nUniversal Credit is incorporating income-related ESA in stages. In the parts of the UK where it already has, contribution-based ESA has been rebadged as \"new-style ESA\".\n\n===Work-Related Activity Group and Support Group===\nAfter the Work Capability Assessment, claimants are split into two groups: the Work-Related Activity Group (WRAG) and the Support Group. In February 2017, 66% of claimants were in the Support Group, 17% were in the WRAG, 13% were in the assessment phase and the phase for 3% of claimants were unknown.<ref name=\"DWPData2017ESA\">{{cite web |title=Quarterly Benefits Summary Data to February 2017 |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/637845/dwp-quarterly-benefit-stats-summary-august-2017.pdf |website=assets.publishing.service.gov.uk |publisher=Department for Work and Pensions |accessdate=2 January 2019 |date=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe WRAG is for claimants who are currently unfit for work but expected to find work in the future. Claimants in the WRAG are required to participate in work-related activity or else they well be sanctioned; where their benefit payments are temporarily stopped. People who are claiming contribution-based ESA and placed in the WRAG are only allowed to claim for one year. WRAG claimants must attend a work-focused interview with a personal advisor, where they discuss how the claimant could find suitable work, and take part in activities to improve their chances of finding work.<ref name=\"CABWRAGESA\">{{cite web |title=About the ESA support group and work-related activity group - Citizens Advice |url=https://www.citizensadvice.org.uk/benefits/sick-or-disabled-people-and-carers/employment-and-support-allowance/while-youre-getting-esa/about-the-esa-groups/ |website=www.citizensadvice.org.uk |publisher=Citizens Advice |accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> Some types of activity claimants may participate in include:<ref name=\"CABWRAGESA\"/>\n\n* Numeracy or literacy courses\n* Learning how to write or improve their [[Curriculum vitae|CV]]\n* Learning how to manage their disability more effectively.\n\nThe support group is for claimants who are not considered fit for work and are unlikely to become fit for work in the near-future. Claimants in this group are paid the support component and are not required to participate in any work-related activity.<ref name=\"CABWRAGESA\"/>\n\n==The claim process==\nSomeone wanting to claim ESA will need a medical certificate, i.e. a sick-note, signed by their GP to say that they are not fully fit for work. The new claimant must then contact the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP), usually by phone,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/employment-support-allowance/how-to-claim |title=Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) |publisher=GOV.UK |date=2015-08-24 |accessdate=2015-08-30 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907154621/https://www.gov.uk/employment-support-allowance/how-to-claim |archivedate=2015-09-07 }}</ref> who will log their claim and usually post them a questionnaire called an ESA50, where the claimant explains how their disability affects them. In rare circumstances, a full assessment is not required, such as when a doctor has officially certified the claimant as being likely to die within six months.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capability-for-work-questionnaire |title=Capability for work questionnaire - Publications |publisher=GOV.UK |date=2013-04-04 |accessdate=2015-08-30 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821005636/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capability-for-work-questionnaire |archivedate=2015-08-21 }}</ref> The completed form must then be sent in the envelope provided to the Health Assessment Advisory Service - the trading name of the assessment provider, [[Maximus Inc.|Maximus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Capability for work questionnaire|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/421191/esa-50-capability-for-work-questionnaire.pdf|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151112214307/https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/421191/esa-50-capability-for-work-questionnaire.pdf|archivedate=2015-11-12}}</ref>\n\nOnce a person has submitted a claim for ESA, they will normally be paid assessment rate for 13 weeks.<ref name=\"WCADWPESA\">{{cite web |title=A guide to Employment and Support Allowance \u2013 The Work Capability Assessment |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/535942/esa214-july-2016.pdf |website=assets.publishing.service.gov.uk |publisher=Department for Work and Pensions |accessdate=1 January 2019 |date=July 2016}}</ref> The ESA50 form, together with any other information sent with it by the claimant, will be read by a qualified healthcare professional, who will then decide on whether a face-to-face medical assessment is actually necessary: some people with severe disabilities can be granted ESA based solely on the documents supplied, if that is clear from the paperwork. For this reason, Maximus encourages new claimants to send as much relevant information as possible and give a detailed description of their disability when filling in the claim form.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chdauk.co.uk/employment-and-support-allowance-esa |title=Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) &#124; Health Assessment Advisory Service |publisher=Chdauk.co.uk |accessdate=2015-08-30 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918045856/https://www.chdauk.co.uk/employment-and-support-allowance-esa |archivedate=2016-09-18 }}</ref> The Claimant is then asked to attend a [[Work Capability Assessment]].<ref name=\"WCADWPESA\"/>\n\n===Assessing capability for work===\n{{Main|Work Capability Assessment}}\n\nThe assessment is often described as consisting of two separate assessments. In practice, if they have a face-to-face assessment, an individual claimant will experience only one assessment on the day (the decision-making is done afterwards). The two stages are:<ref name=\"WCADWPESA\"/>\n\n* The \"limited capability for work\" assessment, which determines whether the claimant is entitled to ESA at all.\n* The \"limited capability for work-related activity\" assessment, which tells the DWP whether somebody who has passed the first stage of the test is able to take part in \"work-related activity\". It also influences the rate of ESA paid to the claimant.\n \nA DWP official makes the final decision on entitlement, based on all the available evidence.\n====Limited capability for work====\nAt their WCA, an ESA claimant must be found to have limited capability for work in order to qualify at all. The testing process gauges the claimant\u2019s ability to perform up to 17 activities; these activities are set out on the ESA claim form. For each activity, a claimant can score 15, 9, 6 or 0 points: the more severe their disability, the more points they will score. Points are scored by having physical impairments, mental ones or a mixture of the two (if they are likely to significantly affect the claimant's ability to work). In order to be entitled to ESA, a person will need to score at least 15 points in total. Other factors, such as some aspects of pregnancy, are also considered by the assessor, who will be a nurse, doctor, occupational therapist or physiotherapist; these factors do not operate on a points system but might nevertheless qualify the claimant for ESA.<ref name=\"WCADWPESA\"/>\n\n====Limited capability for work-related activity====\nThis is about whether a successful claimant of ESA is capable of taking part in interviews and pre-employment training, or whether their ability to do so is limited to a significant degree. As far as the way the WCA actually operates is concerned, this is about whether the claimant has one or more severe disabilities, affecting the 17 areas which the ESA descriptors focus on. If a person is found to have a severe disability, they will be placed in the Support Group.<ref name=\"WCADWPESA\"/>\n\n==Development of ESA==\n\nESA superseded three older benefits: [[Incapacity Benefit]]; [[Income Support]] paid because of an illness or disability; and [[Severe Disablement Allowance]]. \n\n===Early Developments:1998-2007===\nA Green Paper published in 1998 proposed partially means-testing Incapacity Benefit and making deductions from the benefit payments for people receiving an occupational pension.<ref name=LSEESA>{{cite web|url=http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/5553/1/Thatcherism_New_Labour_and_the_Welfare_State.pdf|title=Thatcherism, New Labour and the Welfare State|format=pdf|author=John Hills|date=August 1998|publisher=Centre for Analysis of Social Exclusion: London School of Economics|accessdate=9 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226075526/http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/5553/1/Thatcherism_New_Labour_and_the_Welfare_State.pdf|archivedate=26 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2005, the Welfare Secretary [[Alan Johnson]] announced plans to replace Incapacity Benefit with two new benefits: \"Disability and Sickness Allowance\", for people deemed too ill to work; and \"Rehabilitation Support Allowance\", paid at the same rate as Jobseekers Allowance to less disabled people, who would be supported by the DWP back into work.<ref name=BBCIBESA>{{cite web|date=2 February 2005|publisher=BBC News|title=Incapacity Benefit to be replaced|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4227991.stm|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202134224/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4227991.stm|archivedate=2 December 2008}}</ref> No benefits with these names ever materialised.\n\nIn March 2005, [[Atos]] was awarded the contract to work with the DWP to build the software programme that would be used in the assessment of claims for the allowance that would take the place of Incapacity Benefit. The firm, which was already carrying out the DWP's existing disability assessments, would employ hundreds more healthcare professionals to carry out the new test once it went live - in late 2008.<ref>{{cite web|date=18 March 2005|title=DWP hires Atos Origin to provide medical assessments|publisher=Personnel Today|url=http://www.personneltoday.com/hr/dwp-hires-atos-origin-to-provide-medical-assessments/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018073433/http://www.personneltoday.com/hr/dwp-hires-atos-origin-to-provide-medical-assessments/|archivedate=18 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2006, [[John Hutton, Baron Hutton of Furness|John Hutton]] published a White Paper outlining the government's latest plans for welfare reform: the benefit that would replace Incapacity Benefit would be called Employment and Support Allowance and its gateway assessment would be transformed. Over 10 years, Hutton expected the number of people on Incapacity Benefit to fall by one million, thereby saving \u00a37 billion a year.<ref>{{cite web|title=A new deal for welfare: empowering people to work |publisher=White Paper |date=January 2006 |url=http://dwp.gov.uk/docs/a-new-deal-for-welfare-empowering-people-to-work-full-document.pdf |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130128102031/http://dwp.gov.uk/docs/a-new-deal-for-welfare-empowering-people-to-work-full-document.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-28 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4641588.stm |title=UK Politics &#124; Hutton unveils benefits shake-up |publisher=BBC News |date=2006-01-24 |accessdate=2015-08-30 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909145730/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4641588.stm |archivedate=2017-09-09 }}</ref> The resulting [[Welfare Reform Act 2007|Welfare Reform Bill]] was introduced to Parliament for consideration in July 2006. On 3 May 2007, the bill received royal assent.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=BBC News|date=10 May 2007|title=Blair will stand down on 27 June|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6639945.stm|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071023012828/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6639945.stm|archivedate=23 October 2007}}</ref>\n\nBlair appointed [[David Freud]], as an advisor on out-of-work benefit reform in December 2006. Freud wrote the report: ''Reducing dependency, increasing opportunity: options for the future of welfare to work'' in 2007. It called for the greater use of private sector companies who would be paid by results, for substantial resources to be made available to help people on [[Incapacity Benefit]] back into work, and for a single [[working age]] benefit payment to replace Housing Benefit, Jobseekers Allowance and all other working-age benefits.<ref name=\"FreudReportESA\">{{cite web| title=Freud Report| url=https://www2.learningandwork.org.uk/sites/default/files/policy_downloads/freud_review.pdf| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509091630/https://www2.learningandwork.org.uk/sites/default/files/policy_downloads/freud_review.pdf| archivedate=2016-05-09| access-date=2016-04-26}}</ref><ref name=\"GovFreudESA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/lord-freud|title=The Rt Hon Lord Freud|work=www.gov.uk|accessdate=17 September 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909154230/https://www.gov.uk/government/people/lord-freud|archivedate=9 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"FreudUCESA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.york.ac.uk/inst/spru/research/art/RSjpsj1feb14.pdf|title=Talking Universal Credit: In conversation with Lord Freud, Minister for Welfare Reform|author=Roy Sainsbury|format=pdf|date=2014|publisher=Policy Research Unit, University of York|accessdate=7 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060243/http://www.york.ac.uk/inst/spru/research/art/RSjpsj1feb14.pdf|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2008 a Green Paper was published. It declared that \"between 2009 and 2013, all Incapacity Benefit claimants will be reassessed using a medical assessment called the Work Capability Assessment\" that would divide them into three groups: fit for work; unfit for work but fit for \"work-related activity\"; or fit for neither.<ref>{{cite web|date=July 2008|title=No one written off: reforming welfare to reward responsibility|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/238741/7363.pdf|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160119021619/https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/238741/7363.pdf|archivedate=2016-01-19}}</ref>\n\n====ESA introduced====\nIn October 2008, ESA and its eligibility test, the [[Work Capability Assessment]], were introduced for new claims.<ref>{{cite web |author=Editorial |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/nov/23/welfare-benefits-economy |title=The benefits of welfare reform outweigh the risks |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=2015-08-30 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723182724/http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/nov/23/welfare-benefits-economy |archivedate=2015-07-23 }}</ref> The Welfare Secretary wrote that these and other planned changes would ensure that \"only those who are genuinely incapable of work\" would get full ESA - other sickness benefit recipients would have to comply with plans drawn up with the DWP's private partners to get them back to work.<ref>{{cite web|title=Raising expectations and increasing support: reforming welfare for the future|publisher=DWP|date=December 2008|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/238683/7506.pdf|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018073630/https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/238683/7506.pdf|archivedate=2016-10-18}}</ref> The [[Department for Work and Pensions]] (DWP) contracted [[Atos]] to perform the WCA when it introduced ESA.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-31590017 |title=Work capability assessments: One million disability checks planned - BBC News |publisher=BBC.co.uk |accessdate=2015-08-30 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150827080419/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-31590017 |archivedate=2015-08-27 }}</ref> In December 2008, [[Paul Gregg (academic)|Paul Gregg]] published a report that recommended that most people on ESA should have to undertake work-related activity.<ref>{{cite web|date=December 2008|title=Fair rules for welfare reforms|author=Bristol University|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2008/6040.html|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160702020849/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2008/6040.html|archivedate=2016-07-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Raising expectations and increasing support: reforming welfare for the future|publisher=DWP|date=December 2008|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/238683/7506.pdf|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018073630/https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/238683/7506.pdf|archivedate=2016-10-18}}</ref>\n\n===Coalition 2010\u20132015===\nIn early 2011, the Incapacity Benefit reassessment programme got underway using a more stringent version of the WCA and the caseload's falling trend resumed - until the middle of 2013, when the caseload began to grow again after fresh guidance had to be issued on how to judge fitness for work. By 2015, in the absence of the huge fall in recipients prophesied by the architects of ESA, and in spite of the broadly downward natural long-term trend, the total caseload was little different from when ESA was introduced.<ref>{{cite web|title=Quarterly Benefits Summary|date=May 2015|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/477328/dwp-stats-summary-nov-2015.pdf|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201165033/https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/477328/dwp-stats-summary-nov-2015.pdf|archivedate=2016-02-01}}</ref>\n\nMaximus took over the contract - worth \u00a3170million a year to the US firm - from Atos in March 2015.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\n===2016-Present===\nIn 2016, [[Stephen Crabb]], who was the secretary of state for the DWP, declared that there would be no new welfare policies, other than those set out in the Conservative Party manifesto of 2015, in that parliamentary term. In October 2016, [[Damian Green]] announced a consultation exercise on reforming the WCA.<ref name=BBCGreenESA>{{cite news|title=Work capability assessment overhaul for disabled|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-37810701|publisher=BBC News|date=31 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225190230/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-37810701|archivedate=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Underpayments====\nRoughly 70,000 claimants were paid between \u00a35,000 and \u00a320,000 too little from 2011 to 2016 because the DWP miscalculated their entitlement when they were moved from incapacity benefit on to employment and support allowance.  A [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] report accused the DWP of haste over the transfer while failing to take legal advice or make basic checks. Evidence that people were underpaid was disregarded and warnings from its own policy advisors that it should delay and sort out the issues before proceeding were ignored.  The report said the DWP\u2019s lack of urgency - it took six years to start to deal with the error - showed \u201ca culture of indifference\u201d to people being paid too little. [[Meg Hillier]] said the affair demonstrated \u201cweakness at the highest levels\u201d of the DWP. \u201cThousands of people have not received money essential for living costs because of government\u2019s blinkered and wholly inept handling of ESA\u201d she said.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/jul/18/disability-claimants-owed-340m-after-dwp-blunder-say-mps Disability claimants owed \u00a3340m after DWP blunder, say MPs] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n{{Main|Criticism of Employment Support Allowance}}{{Excessive citations|section|date=November 2019}}\nESA has been criticised for numerous reasons, including claims that the WCA was poorly designed,<ref>{{cite web|title=Litchfield Review 2014|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/380027/wca-fifth-independent-review.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.parliament.uk/writtenevidence/committeeevidence.svc/evidencedocument/work-and-pensions-committee/pip-and-esa-assessments/oral/76113.pdf|title=Dr P Litchfield, evidence to parliament|date=20 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian 22Feb2011\">{{cite news|author=Amelia Gentleman |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2011/feb/22/new-disability-test-is-a-complete-mess |title=New Disability Test is a Complete Mess |publisher=Guardian |date= 22 February 2011|accessdate=30 January 2012 |location=London}}</ref> that WCA and the criteria used to determine fitness for work did not offer a realistic perspective on a claimant's ability to work,<ref name=GeigerESA2>{{cite web|last=Geiger|first=Ben|title=Improving welfare tests should not be beyond the wit of ministers| publisher=Total Politic