{"title_page": "Vulcain (watch company)", "text_new": "{{coord|46.16629|6.11211|display=title}}\n{{short description|Swiss luxury watch manufacturer}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Vulcain\n| logo                = Logo_Vulcain_Watches.jpg\n| logo_size           = 200px\n| type                = [[Private Company|Private]]\n| industry            = Luxury [[watchmaking]]\n| foundation          = 1858 (Manufacture Ditisheim.)<br />1894 (Vulcain)\n| founder             = [[Ditisheim|Maurice Ditisheim]]\n| location            = [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]], [[Canton of Neuch\u00e2tel]], [[Switzerland]]\n| area_served         = Worldwide\n| key_people          = Bernard Fleury\n| products            = Watches\n| production          = 3,000 (2018)<ref name=\"Watch Insider\">{{Cite news|url=https://watch-insider.com/economy/figures-figures-figures-estimated-watches-sold-estimated-turnover-major-watch-brands-switzerland-germany/|title=Estimated Watches Sold And Estimated Turnover Of The Major Watch Brands In Switzerland And Germany (Updated 09.06.2013 & 06.08.2013)|date=2013|work=Watch Insider|access-date=2020-04-04|language=en}}</ref>\n| revenue             = \n| operating_income    = \n| net_income          = \n| num_employees       = 12\n| parent              = Excellence Holding\n| subsid              = \n| footnotes           = \n| homepage            = {{URL|vulcain.ch}}\n}}\n\n'''Vulcain''' is a [[Swiss watch|Swiss Watchmaker]] that was founded in 1858 by [[Ditisheim|Maurice Ditisheim]] as ''Manufacture Ditisheim' in [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]],'' being rebranded as Vulcain in 1894. In 1947, Vulcain developed the first [[Watch|alarm watch]], the Vulcain Cricket.\n== Foundation ==\n\nVulcain was founded in 1858 in [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]], [[Switzerland]] by the [[Ditisheim]] family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.horlogerie-suisse.com/marques/vulcain|title=Vulcain - Les marques|website=Horlogerie Suisse|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> In the family studio, [[Ditisheim]] made [[pocket watch|pocket watches]], which he sold under his own name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mb.nawcc.org/threads/vulcain-pocket-watch-any-info-at-all-v-welcome.49122/|title=Vulcain Pocket Watch, Any info at all v. welcome!|website=NAWCC Message Board|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Through to the end of the Century, the watchmaker was called \"''Manufacture Ditisheim\"''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hodkin|first=Thomas|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vTG_CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA196&lpg=PA196&dq=Manufacture+Ditisheim&source=bl&ots=Enpz8rWZFt&sig=ACfU3U1KmB-lEEI3QjIkIwukBItPAs_cQg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiM0YH5s9noAhWJYMAKHdjUD9sQ6AEwDHoECAwQKQ#v=onepage&q=Manufacture%20Ditisheim&f=false|title=Collecting Clocks Clock Repairs & Trademarks Index|date=2015-04-20|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-1-326-25249-6|language=en}}</ref> In [[1894]], watches were first offered under the branding of ''Vulcain,'' with the company now under the leadership of [[Ditisheim|Maurice Ditisheim's]] son, Ernest-Albert Ditisheim.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Haines|first=Reyne|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HhJjDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT581&lpg=PT581&dq=vulcain+1894&source=bl&ots=V0O5F8_M3t&sig=ACfU3U0ILDp0qxIN9ZB5ULL6SWewQNTMug&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiz1KuHtNnoAhXai1wKHQVQBNkQ6AEwD3oECBEQKQ#v=onepage&q=vulcain%201894&f=false|title=Vintage Wristwatches|date=2010-03-15|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-1-4402-1524-7|language=en}}</ref> In [[1900]], [[Ditisheim]] registered the name 'Vulcain' as a brand name for his [[Pocket watch|pocket watches]], naming it after the [[Roman]] god of Fire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://monochrome-watches.com/old-school-vulcain-cricket/|title=Old School \u2013 Vulcain Cricket|date=2011-08-17|website=Monochrome Watches|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nUp until [[World War II]], Vulcain solely focused on the production of [[Pocket watch|Pocket watches]], only turning to wristwatches with the uptake in popularity of wristwatches for the [[military]].\n\n=== The Alarm Watch ===\nIn the early 1940s, Vulcain invented the idea of a [[Mechanical watch|mechanical alarm watch]]. There had been two prior attempts by other watchmakers in the early [[19th century]], but these projects were failures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timepiecechronicle.com/features/2017/1/17/full-alert-a-history-of-alarm-watches|title=Full Alert: A History of Alarm Watches|website=Timepiece Chronicle|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 1942, Vulcain had begun production of a prototype alarm [[Movement (clockwork)|movement]], later named the 120.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ranfft.de/cgi-bin/bidfun-db.cgi?10&ranfft&&2uswk&Vulcain_120|title=bidfun-db Archive: Watch Movements: Vulcain 120 Cricket|website=www.ranfft.de|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The Caliber 120 could sound for above 20 seconds when fully would through the invention of the 'dual barrel'. This system ensured two separate [[Barrel (horology)|barrels]], which contain the wound up springs generating energy for the watch. These barrels separately provided energy for the [[Movement (clockwork)|movement]], and for the [[Alarm device|alarm]]; hence ensuring that the watch could sound for significantly longer than prior iterations. \n\nThe development of the volume, developed alongside French [[Physisist]] [[Paul Langevin]] took a further 5 years, when Vulcain patented a double-case design to reverberate the sound further.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watchuseek.com/the-presidents-watch-history-and-review-of-vulcain-alarm-watch/|title=The Presidents\u2019 Watch \u2013 History and Review of Vulcain Alarm Watch|last=February 15|first=Bhanu Chopra on|last2=2016|date=2016-02-15|website=watchuseek.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watchcollectinglifestyle.com/home/news-vulcain-cricket-president-edition-france-50-piece-limited-edition|title=News: Vulcain Cricket President 'Edition France'. 50-Piece Limited Edition.|website=WATCH COLLECTING LIFESTYLE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The sound of the alarm notably sounded similar to that of a [[Cricket (insect)|cricket]], with the insect serving as it's namesake.\n\nThe Cricket, released in 1947, ran off of the final iteration of the Caliber 120, which was 17 -[[Watch jewel|Jewels]], had a near two-day power reserved and beat at 18,000 Beats per hour.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Presidential tradition ==\nVulcain gained brand recognition from the early 1950's for their invention of the [[Watch|alarm watch]] - the Vulcain [[Cricket]], which was presented at a Swiss Watch Fair in [[1947]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fratellowatches.com/tbt-worlds-first-alarm-wrist-watch-vulcain-cricket/|title=#TBT World's first alarm wrist watch Vulcain Cricket|date=2019-06-13|website=Fratello Watches|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.onewheee.com/vulcain-cricket-1947-heritage-replica-hands/|title=Vulcain Cricket 1947 Heritage Replica Hands On|date=2017-11-06|website=OneWheee|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shop.analogshift.com/products/vulcain-cricket|title=Vulcain Cricket|website=Analog/Shift|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, The [[White House Correspondents' Association|White House Press Photographer\u2019s Association]] presented [[Harry S. Truman]] with a [[14kt gold|14k gold]] version of the watch on the eve of his leaving presidential office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timepiecechronicle.com/features/2016/6/20/the-vulcain-cricket-made-for-men-worn-by-presidents|title=The Vulcain Cricket: Made for Men, Worn by Presidents|website=Timepiece Chronicle|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.crownandcaliber.com/vulcain-cricket/|title=The Vulcain Cricket: The Watch of Presidents|last=Crown & Caliber|date=2017-02-17|website=Crown & Caliber Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://historical.ha.com/itm/political/presidential-relics/harry-s-truman-personally-owned-vulcain-cricket-wrist-watch/a/6126-42139.s|title=Harry S Truman: Personally Owned Vulcain Cricket Wrist Watch.... {{!}} Lot #42139|website=Heritage Auctions|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Following from this, nearly every President has been gifted one to commemorate their leaving office.\n\nThe Cricket also served as an adventurers watch, as the brand in [[Le Locle]] had partnered with multiple [[mountaineering]] and [[Maritime history|maritime expeditions]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://world.vulcain-watches.ch/en/world/adventure/|title=Adventure: Vulcain|website=world.vulcain-watches.ch|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watchtime.com/featured/watch-u-s-presidents-timepieces/|title=First Watch: U.S. Presidents and Their Timepieces|last=Buchanan|first=Written byNorma|date=2020-02-17|website=WatchTime - USA's No.1 Watch Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=07be13b0-79cf-11ea-8fd1-9bc65fb8c932&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAxNi0xMi0wOC90cnVtcC10by1nZXQtaW5hdWd1cmFsLXRpbWVwaWVjZS1mcm9tLWFpbGluZy1zd2lzcy13YXRjaG1ha2Vy|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-05-06/a-mechanical-alarm-watch-that-every-president-owns|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bloomberg.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== The Extended Watch Range ==\nVulcain, introduced the ''Cricket Nautical'' in 1961.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hodinkee.com/articles/a-week-on-the-wrist-vulcain-nautical-cricket|title=A Week On The Wrist: The Vulcain Nautical Cricket|last=November 07|first=Blake Buettner|last2=2012|website=HODINKEE|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timepiecechronicle.com/features/2017/1/25/designed-to-go-where-we-at-not-the-vulcain-cricket-nautical|title=Designed to go where we at not: The Vulcain Cricket Nautical|website=Timepiece Chronicle|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The watch [[Alarm device|alarm]] was marketed as being audible underwater.<ref>{{Citation|last=Gaillard|first=Aur\u00e9lia|title=Vulcain et sa forge aux xviie et xviiie si\u00e8cles\u00a0: Vulcain d\u00e9senchant\u00e9, Volcan enchant\u00e9 \u2013 d'un imaginaire \u00e0 l'autre|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.4000/books.pur.30843|work=L'imaginaire du volcan|pages=115\u2013131|publisher=Presses universitaires de Rennes|isbn=978-2-7535-0023-5|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.europastar.com/magazine/highlights/1004084736-vulcain-the-cricket-conquers.html|title=Vulcain \u2013 The Cricket conquers|last=Strandberg|first=Keith W.|website=www.europastar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== The Quartz Crisis ==\n\n[[1961]] the companies [[Revue]], [[Vulcain]], [[Buser]] and [[Ph\u00e9nix]] merged to form the \"Manufactures d'Horlogerie Suisse R\u00e9unis SA\" (MSR).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.watchisthis.com/buser-freres-cie-s-a-a-brief-introduction/|title=Buser Fr\u00e8res & Cie S.A. \u2013 A Brief Introduction|website=www.watchisthis.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nDuring the so-called [[quartz crisis]] in the 1980s, Vulcain struggled as the market for high-quality luxury mechanical [[Wristwatch|wristwatches]] collapsed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.montredo.com/en-gb/the-quartz-crisis/|title=The Quartz Crisis: The almost-downfall of the mechanical watch|date=2019-07-24|website=Montredo|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The future was seen to belong to cheap [[Quartz watch|quartz watches]]. Vulcain still produced their watches for sister brands within the [[MSR]], but had a temporary break in manufacture. When the Cricket was produced again under the name of \"[[Revue Thommen]]\", this was done in [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swissluxurywatches.ch/product-category/revue-thommen/|title=Revue Thommen Watches At Discount Prices|website=Swiss Luxury Watches|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Restart of the brand Vulcain under the PMH (Production et Marketing Horologer) ==\n\nTowards the end of the [[1990]]<nowiki/>s, Vulcain was sold by MSR. After it's bankruptcy at the end of the 1990s, the PMH (Production et marketing Horologer) acquired all rights to the brand and the Vulcain Cricket V10 was introduced in [[2001]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watch-wiki.net/index.php?title=Vulcain_Cricket|title=Vulcain Cricket - Watch Wiki: The Best Watches and Watch Brands|website=www.watch-wiki.net|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nThis new beginning was associated with the relocation from [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]] to [[Le Locle]], known for it's association with the watch industry.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Haines, Reyne.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/767501001|title=Vintage Wristwatches.|date=2010|publisher=F+W Media|isbn=978-1-4402-1524-7|location=Cincinnati|oclc=767501001}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/la-chaux-de-fonds-city-of-watchmakers/a-45343653|title=La Chaux-de-Fonds - City of watchmakers {{!}} DW {{!}} 11.09.2018|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche|website=DW.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2002]], the first new models of the Vulcain were presented, largely based on historical models. <ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.vulcain-watches.com/ Vulcain (company website)]\n\n[[Category:Watch brands]]\n[[Category:Le Locle]]\n[[Category:La Chaux-de-Fonds]]\n[[Category:Le Locle]]\n[[Category:La Chaux-de-Fonds]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|46.16629|6.11211|display=title}}\n{{short description|Swiss luxury watch manufacturer}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Vulcain\n| logo                = Logo_Vulcain_Watches.jpg\n| logo_size           = 200px\n| type                = [[Private Company|Private]]\n| industry            = Luxury [[watchmaking]]\n| foundation          = 1858 (Manufacture Ditisheim.)<br />1894 (Vulcain)\n| founder             = [[Ditisheim|Maurice Ditisheim]]\n| location            = [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]], [[Canton of Neuch\u00e2tel]], [[Switzerland]]\n| area_served         = Worldwide\n| key_people          = Bernard Fleury\n| products            = Watches\n| production          = 3,000 (2018)<ref name=\"Watch Insider\">{{Cite news|url=https://watch-insider.com/economy/figures-figures-figures-estimated-watches-sold-estimated-turnover-major-watch-brands-switzerland-germany/|title=Estimated Watches Sold And Estimated Turnover Of The Major Watch Brands In Switzerland And Germany (Updated 09.06.2013 & 06.08.2013)|date=2013|work=Watch Insider|access-date=2020-04-04|language=en}}</ref>\n| revenue             = \n| operating_income    = \n| net_income          = \n| num_employees       = 12\n| parent              = Excellence Holding\n| subsid              = \n| footnotes           = \n| homepage            = {{URL|vulcain.ch}}\n}}\n\n'''Vulcain''' is a [[Swiss watch|Swiss Watchmaker]] that was founded in 1858 by [[Ditisheim|Maurice Ditisheim]] as ''Manufacture Ditisheim' in [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]],'' being rebranded as Vulcain in 1894. In 1947, Vulcain developed the first [[Watch|alarm watch]], the Vulcain Cricket.\n== Foundation ==\n\nVulcain was founded in 1858 in [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]], [[Switzerland]] by the [[Ditisheim]] family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.horlogerie-suisse.com/marques/vulcain|title=Vulcain - Les marques|website=Horlogerie Suisse|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> In the family studio, [[Ditisheim]] made [[pocket watch|pocket watches]], which he sold under his own name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mb.nawcc.org/threads/vulcain-pocket-watch-any-info-at-all-v-welcome.49122/|title=Vulcain Pocket Watch, Any info at all v. welcome!|website=NAWCC Message Board|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Through to the end of the Century, the watchmaker was called \"''Manufacture Ditisheim\"''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hodkin|first=Thomas|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vTG_CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA196&lpg=PA196&dq=Manufacture+Ditisheim&source=bl&ots=Enpz8rWZFt&sig=ACfU3U1KmB-lEEI3QjIkIwukBItPAs_cQg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiM0YH5s9noAhWJYMAKHdjUD9sQ6AEwDHoECAwQKQ#v=onepage&q=Manufacture%20Ditisheim&f=false|title=Collecting Clocks Clock Repairs & Trademarks Index|date=2015-04-20|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-1-326-25249-6|language=en}}</ref> In [[1894]], watches were first offered under the branding of ''Vulcain,'' with the company now under the leadership of [[Ditisheim|Maurice Ditisheim's]] son, Ernest-Albert Ditisheim.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Haines|first=Reyne|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HhJjDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT581&lpg=PT581&dq=vulcain+1894&source=bl&ots=V0O5F8_M3t&sig=ACfU3U0ILDp0qxIN9ZB5ULL6SWewQNTMug&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiz1KuHtNnoAhXai1wKHQVQBNkQ6AEwD3oECBEQKQ#v=onepage&q=vulcain%201894&f=false|title=Vintage Wristwatches|date=2010-03-15|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-1-4402-1524-7|language=en}}</ref> In [[1900]], [[Ditisheim]] registered the name 'Vulcain' as a brand name for his [[Pocket watch|pocket watches]], naming it after the [[Roman]] god of Fire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://monochrome-watches.com/old-school-vulcain-cricket/|title=Old School \u2013 Vulcain Cricket|date=2011-08-17|website=Monochrome Watches|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nUp until [[World War II]], Vulcain solely focused on the production of [[Pocket watch|Pocket watches]], only turning to wristwatches with the uptake in popularity of wristwatches for the [[military]].\n\n=== The Alarm Watch ===\nIn the early 1940s, Vulcain invented the idea of a [[Mechanical watch|mechanical alarm watch]]. There had been two prior attempts by other watchmakers in the early [[19th century]], but these projects were failures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timepiecechronicle.com/features/2017/1/17/full-alert-a-history-of-alarm-watches|title=Full Alert: A History of Alarm Watches|website=Timepiece Chronicle|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 1942, Vulcain had begun production of a prototype alarm [[Movement (clockwork)|movement]], later named the 120.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ranfft.de/cgi-bin/bidfun-db.cgi?10&ranfft&&2uswk&Vulcain_120|title=bidfun-db Archive: Watch Movements: Vulcain 120 Cricket|website=www.ranfft.de|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The Caliber 120 could sound for above 20 seconds when fully would through the invention of the 'dual barrel'. This system ensured two separate [[Barrel (horology)|barrels]], which contain the wound up springs generating energy for the watch. These barrels separately provided energy for the [[Movement (clockwork)|movement]], and for the [[Alarm device|alarm]]; hence ensuring that the watch could sound for significantly longer than prior iterations. \n\nThe development of the volume, developed alongside French [[Physisist]] [[Paul Langevin]] took a further 5 years, when Vulcain patented a double-case design to reverberate the sound further.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watchuseek.com/the-presidents-watch-history-and-review-of-vulcain-alarm-watch/|title=The Presidents\u2019 Watch \u2013 History and Review of Vulcain Alarm Watch|last=February 15|first=Bhanu Chopra on|last2=2016|date=2016-02-15|website=watchuseek.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watchcollectinglifestyle.com/home/news-vulcain-cricket-president-edition-france-50-piece-limited-edition|title=News: Vulcain Cricket President 'Edition France'. 50-Piece Limited Edition.|website=WATCH COLLECTING LIFESTYLE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The sound of the alarm notably sounded similar to that of a [[Cricket (insect)|cricket]], with the insect serving as it's namesake.\n\nThe Cricket, released in 1947, ran off of the final iteration of the Caliber 120, which was 17 -[[Watch jewel|Jewels]], had a near two-day power reserved and beat at 18,000 Beats per hour.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Presidential tradition ==\nVulcain gained brand recognition from the early 1950's for their invention of the [[Watch|alarm watch]] - the Vulcain [[Cricket]], which was presented at a Swiss Watch Fair in [[1947]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fratellowatches.com/tbt-worlds-first-alarm-wrist-watch-vulcain-cricket/|title=#TBT World's first alarm wrist watch Vulcain Cricket|date=2019-06-13|website=Fratello Watches|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.onewheee.com/vulcain-cricket-1947-heritage-replica-hands/|title=Vulcain Cricket 1947 Heritage Replica Hands On|date=2017-11-06|website=OneWheee|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shop.analogshift.com/products/vulcain-cricket|title=Vulcain Cricket|website=Analog/Shift|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, The [[White House Correspondents' Association|White House Press Photographer\u2019s Association]] presented [[Harry S. Truman]] with a [[14kt gold|14k gold]] version of the watch on the eve of his leaving presidential office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timepiecechronicle.com/features/2016/6/20/the-vulcain-cricket-made-for-men-worn-by-presidents|title=The Vulcain Cricket: Made for Men, Worn by Presidents|website=Timepiece Chronicle|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.crownandcaliber.com/vulcain-cricket/|title=The Vulcain Cricket: The Watch of Presidents|last=Crown & Caliber|date=2017-02-17|website=Crown & Caliber Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://historical.ha.com/itm/political/presidential-relics/harry-s-truman-personally-owned-vulcain-cricket-wrist-watch/a/6126-42139.s|title=Harry S Truman: Personally Owned Vulcain Cricket Wrist Watch.... {{!}} Lot #42139|website=Heritage Auctions|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Following from this, nearly every President was been gifted one to commemorate their leaving office.\n\nThe Cricket also served as an adventurers watch, as the brand in [[Le Locle]] had partnered with multiple [[mountaineering]] and [[Maritime history|maritime expeditions]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://world.vulcain-watches.ch/en/world/adventure/|title=Adventure: Vulcain|website=world.vulcain-watches.ch|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watchtime.com/featured/watch-u-s-presidents-timepieces/|title=First Watch: U.S. Presidents and Their Timepieces|last=Buchanan|first=Written byNorma|date=2020-02-17|website=WatchTime - USA's No.1 Watch Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=07be13b0-79cf-11ea-8fd1-9bc65fb8c932&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAxNi0xMi0wOC90cnVtcC10by1nZXQtaW5hdWd1cmFsLXRpbWVwaWVjZS1mcm9tLWFpbGluZy1zd2lzcy13YXRjaG1ha2Vy|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-05-06/a-mechanical-alarm-watch-that-every-president-owns|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bloomberg.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== The Extended Watch Range ==\nVulcain, introduced the ''Cricket Nautical'' in 1961.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hodinkee.com/articles/a-week-on-the-wrist-vulcain-nautical-cricket|title=A Week On The Wrist: The Vulcain Nautical Cricket|last=November 07|first=Blake Buettner|last2=2012|website=HODINKEE|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timepiecechronicle.com/features/2017/1/25/designed-to-go-where-we-at-not-the-vulcain-cricket-nautical|title=Designed to go where we at not: The Vulcain Cricket Nautical|website=Timepiece Chronicle|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The watch [[Alarm device|alarm]] was marketed as being audible underwater.<ref>{{Citation|last=Gaillard|first=Aur\u00e9lia|title=Vulcain et sa forge aux xviie et xviiie si\u00e8cles\u00a0: Vulcain d\u00e9senchant\u00e9, Volcan enchant\u00e9 \u2013 d'un imaginaire \u00e0 l'autre|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.4000/books.pur.30843|work=L'imaginaire du volcan|pages=115\u2013131|publisher=Presses universitaires de Rennes|isbn=978-2-7535-0023-5|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.europastar.com/magazine/highlights/1004084736-vulcain-the-cricket-conquers.html|title=Vulcain \u2013 The Cricket conquers|last=Strandberg|first=Keith W.|website=www.europastar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== The Quartz Crisis ==\n\n[[1961]] the companies [[Revue]], [[Vulcain]], [[Buser]] and [[Ph\u00e9nix]] merged to form the \"Manufactures d'Horlogerie Suisse R\u00e9unis SA\" (MSR).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.watchisthis.com/buser-freres-cie-s-a-a-brief-introduction/|title=Buser Fr\u00e8res & Cie S.A. \u2013 A Brief Introduction|website=www.watchisthis.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nDuring the so-called [[quartz crisis]] in the 1980s, Vulcain struggled as the market for high-quality luxury mechanical [[Wristwatch|wristwatches]] collapsed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.montredo.com/en-gb/the-quartz-crisis/|title=The Quartz Crisis: The almost-downfall of the mechanical watch|date=2019-07-24|website=Montredo|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The future was seen to belong to cheap [[Quartz watch|quartz watches]]. Vulcain still produced their watches for sister brands within the [[MSR]], but had a temporary break in manufacture. When the Cricket was produced again under the name of \"[[Revue Thommen]]\", this was done in [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swissluxurywatches.ch/product-category/revue-thommen/|title=Revue Thommen Watches At Discount Prices|website=Swiss Luxury Watches|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Restart of the brand Vulcain under the PMH (Production et Marketing Horologer) ==\n\nTowards the end of the [[1990]]<nowiki/>s, Vulcain was sold by MSR. After it's bankruptcy at the end of the 1990s, the PMH (Production et marketing Horologer) acquired all rights to the brand and the Vulcain Cricket V10 was introduced in [[2001]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watch-wiki.net/index.php?title=Vulcain_Cricket|title=Vulcain Cricket - Watch Wiki: The Best Watches and Watch Brands|website=www.watch-wiki.net|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nThis new beginning was associated with the relocation from [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]] to [[Le Locle]], known for it's association with the watch industry.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Haines, Reyne.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/767501001|title=Vintage Wristwatches.|date=2010|publisher=F+W Media|isbn=978-1-4402-1524-7|location=Cincinnati|oclc=767501001}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/la-chaux-de-fonds-city-of-watchmakers/a-45343653|title=La Chaux-de-Fonds - City of watchmakers {{!}} DW {{!}} 11.09.2018|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche|website=DW.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2002]], the first new models of the Vulcain were presented, largely based on historical models. <ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.vulcain-watches.com/ Vulcain (company website)]\n\n[[Category:Watch brands]]\n[[Category:Le Locle]]\n[[Category:La Chaux-de-Fonds]]\n[[Category:Le Locle]]\n[[Category:La Chaux-de-Fonds]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vulcain_(watch_company)"}
{"title_page": "Emily Stannard", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Distinguish|text = her daughter Emily Stannard (1827\u201394)}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Emily Stannard\n| image = Emily Stannard.png\n| imagesize = \n| alt = \n| caption = ''Portrait of Mrs Joseph Stannard (1830\u20131885)'' by Julian Cedric Brewer (c. 1885)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://norfolkmuseumscollections.org/collections/objects/object-4250024622.html/#!/?q=emily%2Bstannard|title= Portrait of Emily Stannard|website=Norfolk Museums Collections|accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1802|02|08}}\n| birth_place = [[Norwich]], England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|1885|01|06|1802|02|08}}\n| death_place = Norwich, England\n| nationality = British\n| field = [[still life]] painting\n| training = \n| movement = [[Norwich School of painters]]\n| spouse           = [[Joseph Stannard]]\n| works = \n| patrons = \n| influenced by = \n| awards = \n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Emily Stannard''' (n\u00e9e '''Emily Coppin'''; 8 February 1802 \u2013 6 January 1885), also known as '''Mrs Joseph Stannard''', was a British [[still life]] painter. She was associated with the [[Norwich School of painters]], Britain's first provincial [[art movement]]. Along with her niece [[Eloise Harriet Stannard]], she is considered to be the finest British female still life artist of the nineteenth century.\n\nEmily Coppin was born in [[Norwich]], the daughter of [[Daniel Coppin]] and his wife [[Elizabeth Coppin|Elizabeth]] (n\u00e9e Clyatt), who were both accomplished amateur artists. In 1820, she travelled with her father to [[Netherlands|Holland]] to study the paintings of [[Jan van Huysum]] and other [[Dutch Golden Age painting|Dutch masters]], an episode in her life which greatly influenced her work. She married the Norwich artist [[Joseph Stannard]] in 1826, but was widowed four years later, when he succumbed to [[tuberculosis]]. She continued painting until she was in her eighties, mainly depicting still life paintings of flowers in vases, fruit or game animals. Her works were exhibited in both Norwich and London. She was awarded a large gold medal in 1820 for an original painting of flowers and was awarded two further gold medals in later years. She became an honorary member of the Norwich Society of Artists in 1831, the only member of her artistic family to be formally associated with the Society.\n\nThe largest collection of her works are held by the Norfolk Museums Collections, based at [[Norwich Castle]].\n\n==Life==\n{{multiple image\n | direction = horizontal\n | width = 120\n | footer = \n | image1 = Portrait of Joseph Stannard.jpg \n | alt1 = \n | caption1 = Joseph Stannard\n | image2 = Stannard family home, Norwich.jpg\n | alt2 = \n | caption2 = Joseph and Emily Stannard's home in Norwich \n }}\n\nEmily Coppin was born on 8 February 1802 in [[Norwich]], the daughter of [[Daniel Coppin]] and his wife [[Elizabeth Coppin|Elizabeth Clyatt]]. She was baptised at [[St Stephen's Church, Norwich]] on 14 February.<ref>Emily Coppin in \"Archdeacons transcripts for Norwich parishes, 1600\u20131812\", ''FamilySearch'' ([https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/3:1:939X-DYXN-S?i=1683&cc=1824688 Emily Coppin])</ref> Both her parents were accomplished amateur artists.{{sfn|Walpole|1997|p=58}} Daniel Coppin, who was also a collector, was one of the founding members of the Norwich Society of Artists. Her mother was a talented [[copyist]], but Emily far exceeded her artistic ability.{{sfn|Moore|1985|p=96}} According to [[Parish register#England|parish records]] her elder siblings were Frederic Daniel, Henry and Mary Elizabeth, and her younger siblings were Lucy and Edward (all [[Infant baptism|christened]] between 1796 and 1805). Both of Emily's sisters died in infancy.<ref>Search Results from Historical Records, ''FamilySearch'' ([https://www.familysearch.org/search/record/results?count=20&query=%2Bsurname%3Acoppin~%20%2Bbirth_place%3Anorwich~%20%2Bfather_givenname%3Adaniel~])</ref>\n\nAlmost nothing is known of Emily Coppin's childhood or education. In 1820, she travelled with her father to Holland to study Dutch painting, which greatly influenced her subsequent work.{{sfn|Gray|2009|p=249}}{{sfn|Dickes|1905|p=526}} During her visit, she obtained permission to copy paintings by the Dutch Master [[Jan van Huysum]] at Trippon House, Amsterdam, and her work was praised for its accuracy. There, according to her obituary, \"she complied with the conditions laid down by showing two specimens of her painting, the President of the Amsterdam Gallery, Mons. Apostal, expressing great satisfaction with her work, and she was allowed to make a copy of another Van Huysum\".{{sfn|Moore|1988|p=144}}<ref name=\"OBIT\" />\n\nOn 3 January 1826, when already an established artist who had exhibited works, she married the Norwich School painter [[Joseph Stannard]] in St George's Tombland, Norwich.<ref>Emily Coppin in \"England, Norfolk Bishop's Transcripts, 1685\u20131941\", ''FamilySearch'' ([https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:N6BT-ZPP Emily Coppin]).</ref> They were a well-matched couple, with both coming from artistic backgrounds.{{sfn|Moore|1985|p=96}} Their daughter Emily was born in 1827.{{sfn|Gray|2009|p=249}} A second daughter, Harriet Augusta, died in 1830 age 9 months.<ref>Harriet Augusta Stannard in \"England Deaths and Burials, 1538\u20131991\", ''FamilySearch'' ([https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:JDH9-13B Harriet Augusta Stannard]).</ref> The marriage was short-lived, for Joseph Stannard died of [[tuberculosis]] in 1830 at the age of thirty-three, despite the efforts of his wife, who tried many doctors and treatments in an attempt to save him.{{sfn|Walpole|1997|pp=58\u201359}}\n\nStannard continued to live in Norwich for over fifty years, but only the notice she attracted in the press for her paintings gives any impression of her life during this period. According to census records for 1841\u201381 she was residing with her brother-in-law [[Alfred Stannard]] and his family on census night in 1841, but only with her daughter Emily from 1851 to 1881, when her occupation is described as 'Artist' or 'Artist Dead Life'.<ref>Birth, Marriage, & Death, ''FamilySearch'' ([https://www.familysearch.org/search/record/results?count=20&query=%2Bgivenname%3Aemily~%20%2Bsurname%3Astannard~%20%2Bbirth_year%3A1802-1802~%20%2Bfather_givenname%3Adaniel~]).</ref>\n\nDuring her last years she lived at 12, Cathedral Street, Norwich, with her unmarried daughter Emily. She died there on 6 January 1885,<ref name=\"OBIT\">{{cite web |url= https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk|title= Norfolk Chronicle and Norwich Gazette \u2013 Saturday 17 January 1885|author=<!--Not stated--> |year= 2018|website= The British Newspaper Archive|publisher= [[British Library]]|access-date= 7 December 2018}}</ref> her will being proved by her daughter.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk/Calendar?surname=stannard&yearOfDeath=1885&page=3#calendar|title= Find a will|author=<!--Not stated--> |website= |publisher= Government of the United Kingdom|access-date= 7 December 2018}}</ref> Her obituary appeared in the local press the week following her death, mentioning that \"Mrs. Stannard had a great artistic merit, was a very clever painter of fruit, flowers, fish, game, and still life, and her pictures have always been highly esteemed by lovers of art\", and describing \"her kindly, gentle, modest, and simple nature (which) endeared her to all who had the pleasure of her acquaintance\".{{refn|1=Emily Stannard's full obituary in ''The Norfolk Chronicle'' read: \"We regret to announce the somewhat sudden death of a charming old lady, Mrs. Joseph Stannard, of 12, Cathedral-street, in this city, on Tuesday, the 6th inst. Mrs Joseph Stannard, n\u00e9e Coppin, was one of the last remaining links of the old Norwich School of Artists. She was the widow of the well-known and excellent artist, Joseph Stannard, who died in 1830, at the early age of 34 years, in the prime of life, and while rapidly and steadily advancing in power and fame. Mrs. Stannard had a great artistic merit, was a very clever painter of fruit, flowers, fish, game, and still life, and her pictures have always been highly esteemed by lovers of art. In 1820 she received the large gold medal from the Society of Arts for an original painting of flowers. In August of the same year she went with her father to Holland, where in the Hague Gallery she made truthful copies of two precious small fruit pictures. At Trippon House, Amsterdam, she obtained permission to reproduce the celebrated Flower Pictures by Van Huysum. Her copies were greatly praised by celebrated foreign connoisseurs of the day for their close similitude of the originals. At Amsterdam she complied with the conditions laid down by showing two specimens of her painting, the President of the Amsterdam Gallery, Mons. Apostal, expressing great satisfaction with her work, and she was allowed to make a copy of another Van Huysum. In 1821 she was presented with the large gold medal of the Society of Arts, London, for an original painting of fruit. In 1828, as Mrs. Joseph Stannard, she received the gold medal for an original painting of game. As late as 1870 she exhibited in an exhibition at Norwich two very pictures of flowers and song birds, elaborately and beautifully painted, both of them brilliant and effective, which were very highly spoken of in the local journals at the time. Her kindly, gentle, modest, and simple nature endeared her to all who had the pleasure of her acquaintance, by whom she will ever be remembered with great esteem, regard, and affection. Many of the last years of her life were smoothed and cheered by the loving care and companionship of an only daughter, to whom we tender our sincere sympathy\".<ref>{{cite news\n| date         = 17 January 1885\n| title        = The late Mrs. Joseph Stannard\n| url          = https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/search/results/1885-01-17?basicsearch=joseph%20stannard&exactsearch=false&county=norfolk%2c%20england&retrievecountrycounts=false&mostspecificlocation=norfolk%2c%20england&newspapertitle=norfolk%2bchronicle\n|url-access=subscription\n| work    = The Norfolk Chronicle\n| location     = Norwich\n| publisher = The British Newspaper Archive\n| access-date  = 5 April 2019\n}}</ref>|group=note}}\n\nHer gold medals were donated by her daughter to the new museum at [[Norwich Castle]] in 1894.{{sfn|Hill|2016}}{{refn|1=The museum described them as \"Three Gold Medals inscribed the \"Society of Arts and Commerce Promoted\" awarded to Mrs. Joseph Stannard for painting, and the Silver \"Honorary Pallet of the Society for Promoting Arts, Manufacturer and Commerce,\" awarded to Mrs. Coppin for Drawing\".<ref>Norwich Castle Museum Committee (1894), p. 15.</ref> Emily also donated the paintings of her parents and her grandmother Elizabeth Coppin, in what the author Kate Hill described as \"an unusual example of an attempt to memorialise women artists\".{{sfn|Hill|2016}}|group=note}} \n\nEmily Stannard continued to live at Cathedral Street until her death in 1894 at the age of 67.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk|title= Eastern Evening News|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 24 November 1894|website= British Newspaper Archive|access-date= 14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Background===\n{{further|Norwich School of painters}}\n\nThe Norwich School of painters was a unique phenomenon in the history of British 19th century art.{{sfn|Moore|1985|p=9}} [[Norwich]] was the first English city outside London where a school of artists arose.{{sfn|Cundall|1920|p=1}} It had more local-born artists than any subsequently-formed schools elsewhere,{{sfn|Hemingway|1979|pp=9, 79}} its most important artists being [[John Crome]], Emily Stannard's husband [[Joseph Stannard]], [[George Vincent (painter)|George Vincent]], [[Robert Ladbrooke]], [[James Stark (painter)|James Stark]], [[John Thirtle]] and [[John Sell Cotman]].{{sfn|Hemingway|1988|p=17}} The Norwich School artists were connected by geographical location, their depiction of Norwich and rural [[Norfolk]], and by close personal and professional relationships.{{refn|1=The Stannards were the most conspicuous family of still-life painters in nineteenth century England. [[Alfred Stannard]] and his older brother Joseph specialised in painting [[Landscape painting|landscapes]] and [[marine art]], but with the encouragement of Emily Stannard included still-life works in their repertoire. Her niece [[Eloise Harriet Stannard]] in turn became a prominent painter flowers and fruit.{{sfn|Nunn|1995|p=39}}|group=note}} By the end of the 19th century the paintings by the artists of the Norwich School, who had once been regarded as modern and progressive, were seen as belonging to a bygone age, a view that Professor [[Andrew Hemingway (art historian)|Andrew Hemingway]] has attributed to the \"mythology of rural Englishness\" that prevailed at the start of the 20th century.{{sfn|Hemingway|1988|p=30}}\n\nThe Norwich Society of Artists was founded in 1803.{{sfn|Rajnai|Stevens|1976|p=13}} It held annual exhibitions from 1805 to 1825 and again from 1828 until its dissolution in 1833.{{sfn|Rajnai|Stevens|1976|p=4}} Members of the Stannard family showed their pictures at the exhibitions, but they had few other artistic connections with their Norwich contemporaries. Emily Stannard, who became an honorary member of the Society in 1831, was the only member of the Stannard family to have a formal association with the Society.{{sfn|Moore|1985|p=95}}\n\n===Teaching===\n\nEmily, assisted by her daughter, had a career as an art teacher.{{sfn|Gray|2009|p=249}} Hardly any information about this aspect of her life is provided by her past or present biographers.\n\n===Works===\n[[File:Emily-Coppin-Stannard still-life-1824.jpg|thumb|''Floral still life with a silver-gilt cup'' (1824)]]\n[[File:Emily Coppin Stannard - Still Life with Mallard Snipes and Gold Medals.jpg|thumb|''Still Life with Mallard Snipes and Gold Medals'']]\n\nEmily Stannard and her niece [[Eloise Harriet Stannard]] are nowadays considered to be the finest British women still life painters of the nineteenth century.{{sfn|Walpole|1997|pp=58\u201359}} Stannard's early paintings were influenced by the Dutch masters Huysum and De Heem.{{Ambiguous|date=December 2018}}{{sfn|Moore|1985|p=104}} Both her depiction of vases and the finish of her depiction of flowers owed much to Huysum, and her unsigned works were sometimes attributed to 18th century Dutch painters.{{sfn|Mitchell|1973|pp=242\u20134}} ''Still life: Dead Ducks and a Hare with a Basket and Sprig of Holly'' reveals her debt to [[Jan Weenix]], whose work ''Dead Hare and Partidges'' she presumably saw when it was exhibited at the [[British Institution]]. Paintings by Dutch masters at [[English country house|country houses]] in Norfolk (such as at [[Wolterton Hall]]) may also have been available to her.{{sfn|Moore|1988|p=144}}\n\nShe first exhibited her works in 1816.{{sfn|Rajnai|Stevens|1976|p=87}} In 1821, aged seventeen, she was awarded the Norwich Society of Artists' gold medal for one of her flower paintings.{{sfn|Moore|1985|p=96}} She won a second medal the following year for a painting of a collection of fruit.{{sfn|Gray|2009|p=249}} She received a third gold medal in 1828 for a still life of game animals,{{sfn|Mackie|1901|p=354}} which was exhibited at the Norwich Society of Artists as ''Dead Game from Nature''.{{sfn|Rajnai|Stevens|1976|p=87}} Throughout her long career, which continued until shortly before her death at the age of 82, she continued to depict [[Flower bouquet|bouquets of flowers in vases]] and other traditional still life paintings of tableware, fruit or [[Game (hunting)|game animals]], set against monochrome backgrounds.{{sfn|Vincent|1992}}{{sfn|Walpole|1997|pp=58\u20139}}\n\nAlthough she usually exhibited her work in Norwich, she also exhibited paintings at the [[Royal Society of British Artists]] in 1824 and the [[British Institution]] from 1823 to 1825.{{sfn|Gray|2009|p=249}}\n\nAccording to the art historian and author Josephine Walpole, Emily Stannard's paintings display a \"natural talent\" and \"impeccable colour sense\".{{sfn|Walpole|1997|p=58}} According to Andrew Moore, her technique and command of composition strengthened in the years after her husband's death.{{sfn|Moore|1985|p=105}}\n\nOn least one occasion she signed a painting using her Christian name,{{sfn|Mitchell|1973|pp=242\u20134}} but her works are invariably signed 'Mrs. Joseph Stannard'. Her canvasses, which were often left unvarnished, were consistently painted with a thin, diluted paint, in a similar way to the works of the Dutch masters she studied.{{sfn|Moore|1988|p=144}}\n\nThe Norfolk Museums Collections is the only United Kingdom public art collection which possesses works by Emily Stannard. Her paintings there are: ''Still life: hamper with dead wood pigeon and leveret''; ''Still life: dead ducks and a hare with a basket and a sprig of holly'' (1853); ''Still life with dead game and a flagon and a string of onions'' (1847); ''Dead game and a gun'' (1835); ''Dead game'' (1837); ''Flowers''; ''Still life: group of dead game birds''; and ''Wild duck (study)''.{{sfn|Wright| Gordon|2006|p=743}}\n\nPrices paid for her paintings include \u00a3400 for ''Still life study of dead birds on a table oil on board'' in 2017, \u00a31600 for ''Still Life Study of Mixed Flowers and Fruit in Basket on Marble Ledge'' in 2015, \u00a3920 for ''Still Life Study of Mixed Flowers, Birds Nest and Butterfly on Marble Ledge'' in 2015, and \u00a3130 for a [[watercolour painting]] ''Tranquil River Landscape'' in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.keysauctions.co.uk/?s=emily+stannard&lots=1|title= Lot Results for: emily stannard|website= Keys Fine Art Auctioneers|accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref> Her larger painting ''The game larder'' (52 x 43.2&nbsp;cm) was sold at [[Christie's]] in 2013 for \u00a310,000.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.christies.com/lotfinder/Lot/emily-stannard-1803-1885-the-game-larder-5715041-details.aspx|title= Sale 1886 (Lot 483)|website= Christie's|accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist | refs=\n}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book | ref = harv |last= Cundall|first= Herbert Minton|date= 1920|title= The Norwich School|url= https://archive.org/details/cu31924014891992|location= London|publisher= Geoffrey Holme Ltd |page= |isbn= |author-link= }} {{free access}}\n*{{cite book |ref = harv |last=Dickes |first=William Frederick |date=1905 |title=The Norwich school of painting: being a full account of the Norwich exhibitions, the lives of the painters, the lists of their respecitve exhibits and descriptions of the pictures |url= https://archive.org/details/norwichschoolofp00dick/page/524|location= Norwich|publisher= Jarrold & Sons Ltd.|page= |isbn= |author-link= William Dickes}} {{free access}}\n*{{cite book |ref = harv |last= Gray|first= Sara|date= 2009|title= The Dictionary of British Women Artists|url=|location= Cambridge|publisher= Lutterworth Press|page= |isbn= |author-link= }}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Hemingway |first1=Andrew |authorlink1=Andrew Hemingway (art historian) |title=The Norwich School of Painters 1803-1833 |date=1979 |publisher=Phaidon |location=Oxford |isbn=9780714820019 |url=https://archive.org/details/norwichschoolofp00hemi }}\n*{{cite journal | ref = harv |last1= Hemingway|first1= Andrew |author-link1= Andrew Hemingway (art historian)|year= 1988|title= Cultural Philanthropy and the Invention of the Norwich School|journal= Oxford Art Journal|volume= 11|issue= 2|pages=17\u201339}}\n*{{cite book |ref = harv |last= Hill|first= Kate|date= 2016|title= Women and Museums 1850-1914: Modernity and the Gendering of Knowledge|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3o0LDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT89&lpg=PT89&dq=%22Emily+stannard%22+norwich&source=bl&ots=YRHn_xKSb4&sig=zu_hT0kDVdAW534zLIAMp8tx24A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiYvMW16tTeAhVrh4sKHabVCsg4FBDoATAAegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=%22Emily%20stannard%22%20norwich&f=false|location= Cambridge|publisher= Manchester University Press|page= |isbn= 978-0719081156|author-link= }}\n*{{cite book|ref= harv|last= Mackie|first= Charles|date= 1901|title= Norfolk Annals: A Chronological Record of Remarkable Events in the Nineteenth Century Vol. 2 (1851\u20131900)|url= https://archive.org/details/norwichschoolofp00hemi|location= Oxford|publisher= Norfolk Chronicle|page= |isbn= 0-7148-2001-6|author-link= Andrew Hemingway (art historian)}}\n*{{cite book|ref= harv|last= Mitchell|first= Peter|date= 1973|title= Great flower painters; four centuries of floral art|url= https://archive.org/details/greatflowerpaint00mitc|location= Woodstock, New York|publisher= The Overlook Press|page= |isbn= 0-87951-008-0|author-link= }}\n*{{cite book | ref = harv |last1= Moore|first1= Andrew w.|last2=|first2=|date= 1988|title= Dutch and Flemish Painting in Norfolk: A history of taste and influence, fashion and collecting|url= |location= London|publisher= Her Majesty's Stationery Office|page= |isbn= 0 11 701061 8|author-link= }}\n*{{cite book | ref = harv |last= Moore|first= Andrew W.|date= 1985|title= The Norwich School of Artists|url=|location= |publisher= HMSO/Norwich Museums Service|page= |isbn= |author-link= }}\n*{{cite book|ref= harv|last= Nunn|first= Pamela Gerrish|date= 1995|title= Problem Pictures: Women and Men in Victorian Painting|url= https://archive.org/details/problempicturesw0000nunn|location= |publisher= Scolar Press|page= |isbn= 9781859281529|author-link= |url-access= registration}}\n\n*{{cite book | ref = harv |last1= Rajnai|first1= Miklos |author-link1= |last2= Stevens|first2= Mary|author-link2= |last3= |first3= |author-link3= |date= 1976|title= The Norwich Society of Artists, 1805-1833: a dictionary of contributors and their work|url=|location= |publisher= Norfolk Museums Service for the Paul Mellon Centre for Studies in British Art|page= |isbn= |author-link= }}\n*{{cite book |ref = harv |last= Vincent|first= Adrian|date= 1992|title= A Companion to Victorian and Edwardian Artists|url=|location= |publisher= David & Charles|page= |isbn= 1-85149-261-5|author-link= }}\n*{{cite book |ref = harv |last= Walpole|first= Josephine|date= 1997|title= Art and Artists of the Norwich School|url=|location= Woodbridge|publisher= Antique Collectors' Club|page= |isbn= 1-85149-261-5|author-link= }}\n*{{cite book | ref = harv |last1= Wright|first1= Christopher|last2=Gordon|first2=Catherine|date= 2006|title= British and Irish paintings in public collections : an index of British and Irish oil paintings by artists born before 1870 in public and institutional collections in the United Kingdom and Ireland|url= |location= New Haven|publisher= Yale University Press |pages= 790\u20131|isbn= 9780300117301|author-link= }}\n*{{cite book | ref = harv |last1= |first1= |author-link1= |last2= |first2= |author-link2= |last3= |first3= |author-link3= |date= 1894|title= The Report of the Castle Museum Committee to the Town Council |url=https://archive.org/details/reportcastlemus00musegoog/page/n22|location= Norwich|publisher=  Edward Burgess|page= |isbn= |author-link= }}\n*{{cite book | ref = harv |last1= |first1= |author-link1= |last2= |first2= |author-link2= |last3= |first3= |author-link3= |date= 1821|title= Transactions of the Society, Instituted at London for the Encouragement of Arts, Manufactures and Commerce|url=https://play.google.com/store/books/details?id=BsxUAAAAcAAJ&rdid=book-BsxUAAAAcAAJ&rdot=1|volume= 39|edition= 2|location= London|publisher=  Dodsley, Lockyer|page= |isbn= |author-link= }} {{free access}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://norfolkmuseumscollections.org/#!/collections/search?q=emily%2BStannard&mediaType=image 11 works by Emily Coppin Stannard] in the Norfolk Museums Collections\n* [https://suffolkartists.co.uk/index.cgi?choice=painter&pid=4142 ''Emily Stannard''] \u2013 Suffolk Artists website\n* Past auction results for works by Emily Stannard from [https://www.mutualart.com/Artist/Emily-Coppin-Stannard/F4A1631911AD4D42/AuctionResults MutualArt], [https://www.invaluable.co.uk/artist/stannard-emily-6ixe618ohf/sold-at-auction-prices/ Invaluable] and [http://www.artnet.com/artists/emily-coppin-stannard/past-auction-results Artnet]\n* Works by Emily Stannard sold by [http://www.leicestergalleries.com/archives/search/a/EMILY%20COPPIN%20STANNARD%20%20(1803-1885)/1998 The Leicester Galleries] and [https://www.bonhams.com/search/?q=emily%20stannard&main_index_key=lot#/q0=emily%2520stannard&MR0_display=search&m0=0?q=emily%20stannard Bonhams]\n* [https://www.npg.org.uk/assets/files/pdf/research/artists_materials_9_Rowney.pdf Examples of labels] from [[Daler-Rowney|Rowney & Forster]] on the reverse side of paintings by Emily Stannard\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Norwich School of painters}}\n{{Stannard family tree}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stannard, Emily Coppin}}\n[[Category:1802 births]]\n[[Category:1895 deaths]]\n[[Category:British women painters]]\n[[Category:19th-century British women artists]]\n[[Category:British still life painters]]\n[[Category:People from Norwich]]\n[[Category:19th-century British painters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Distinguish|text = her daughter Emily Stannard (1827\u201394)}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Emily Stannard\n| image = Emily Stannard.png\n| imagesize = \n| alt = \n| caption = ''Portrait of Mrs Joseph Stannard (1830\u20131885)'' by Julian Cedric Brewer (c. 1885)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://norfolkmuseumscollections.org/collections/objects/object-4250024622.html/#!/?q=emily%2Bstannard|title= Portrait of Emily Stannard|website=Norfolk Museums Collections|accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1802|02|08}}\n| birth_place = [[Norwich]], England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|1885|01|06|1802|02|08}}\n| death_place = Norwich, England\n| nationality = British\n| field = [[still life]] painting\n| training = \n| movement = [[Norwich School of painters]]\n| spouse           = [[Joseph Stannard]]\n| works = \n| patrons = \n| influenced by = \n| awards = \n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Emily Stannard''' (n\u00e9e '''Emily Coppin'''; 8 February 1802 \u2013 6 January 1885), also known as '''Mrs Joseph Stannard''', was a British [[still life]] painter. She was associated with the [[Norwich School of painters]], Britain's first provincial [[art movement]]. Along with her niece [[Eloise Harriet Stannard]], she is considered to be the finest British female still life artist of the nineteenth century.\n\nEmily Coppin was born in [[Norwich]], the daughter of [[Daniel Coppin]] and his wife [[Elizabeth Coppin|Elizabeth]] (n\u00e9e Clyatt), who were both accomplished amateur artists. In 1820, she travelled with her father to [[Netherlands|Holland]] to study the paintings of [[Jan van Huysum]] and other [[Dutch Golden Age painting|Dutch masters]], an episode in her life which greatly influenced her work. She married the Norwich artist [[Joseph Stannard]] in 1826, but was widowed four years later, when he succumbed to [[tuberculosis]]. She continued painting until she was in her eighties, mainly depicting still life paintings of flowers in vases, fruit or game animals. Her works were exhibited in both Norwich and London. She was awarded a large gold medal in 1820 for an original painting of flowers and was awarded two further gold medals in later years. She became an honorary member of the Norwich Society of Artists in 1831, the only member of her artistic family to be formally associated with the Society.\n\nThe largest collection of her works are held by the Norfolk Museums Collections, based at [[Norwich Castle]].\n\n==Life==\n{{multiple image\n | direction = horizontal\n | width = 120\n | footer = \n | image1 = Portrait of Joseph Stannard.jpg \n | alt1 = \n | caption1 = Joseph Stannard\n | image2 = Stannard family home, Norwich.jpg\n | alt2 = \n | caption2 = Joseph and Emily Stannard's home in Norwich \n }}\n\nEmily Coppin was born on 8 February 1802 in [[Norwich]], the daughter of [[Daniel Coppin]] and his wife [[Elizabeth Coppin|Elizabeth Clyatt]]. She was baptised at [[St Stephen's Church, Norwich]] on 14 February.<ref>Emily Coppin in \"Archdeacons transcripts for Norwich parishes, 1600\u20131812\", ''FamilySearch'' ([https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/3:1:939X-DYXN-S?i=1683&cc=1824688 Emily Coppin])</ref> Both her parents were accomplished amateur artists.{{sfn|Walpole|1997|p=58}} Daniel Coppin, who was also a collector, was one of the founding members of the Norwich Society of Artists. Her mother was a talented [[copyist]], but Emily far exceeded her artistic ability.{{sfn|Moore|1985|p=96}} According to [[Parish register#England|parish records]] her elder siblings were Frederic Daniel, Henry and Mary Elizabeth, and her younger siblings were Lucy and Edward (all [[Infant baptism|christened]] between 1796 and 1805). Both of Emily's sisters died in infancy.<ref>Search Results from Historical Records, ''FamilySearch'' ([https://www.familysearch.org/search/record/results?count=20&query=%2Bsurname%3Acoppin~%20%2Bbirth_place%3Anorwich~%20%2Bfather_givenname%3Adaniel~])</ref>\n\nAlmost nothing is known of Emily Coppin's childhood or education. In 1820, she travelled with her father to Holland to study Dutch painting, which greatly influenced her subsequent work.{{sfn|Gray|2009|p=249}}{{sfn|Dickes|1905|p=526}} During her visit, she obtained permission to copy paintings by the Dutch Master [[Jan van Huysum]] at Trippon House, Amsterdam, and her work was praised for its accuracy. There, according to her obituary, \"she complied with the conditions laid down by showing two specimens of her painting, the President of the Amsterdam Gallery, Mons. Apostal, expressing great satisfaction with her work, and she was allowed to make a copy of another Van Huysum\".{{sfn|Moore|1988|p=144}}<ref name=\"OBIT\" />\n\nOn 3 January 1826, when already an established artist who had exhibited works, she married the Norwich School painter [[Joseph Stannard]] in St George's Tombland, Norwich.<ref>Emily Coppin in \"England, Norfolk Bishop's Transcripts, 1685\u20131941\", ''FamilySearch'' ([https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:N6BT-ZPP Emily Coppin]).</ref> They were a well-matched couple, with both coming from artistic backgrounds.{{sfn|Moore|1985|p=96}} Their daughter Emily was born in 1827.{{sfn|Gray|2009|p=249}} A second daughter, Harriet Augusta, died in 1830 age 9 months.<ref>Harriet Augusta Stannard in \"England Deaths and Burials, 1538\u20131991\", ''FamilySearch'' ([https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:JDH9-13B Harriet Augusta Stannard]).</ref> The marriage was short-lived, for Joseph Stannard died of [[tuberculosis]] in 1830 at the age of thirty-three, despite the efforts of his wife, who tried many doctors and treatments in an attempt to save him.{{sfn|Walpole|1997|pp=58\u201359}}\n\nStannard continued to live in Norwich for over fifty years, but only the notice she attracted in the press for her paintings gives any impression of her life during this period. According to census records for 1841\u201381 she was residing with her brother-in-law [[Alfred Stannard]] and his family on census night in 1841, but only with her daughter Emily from 1851 to 1881, when her occupation is described as 'Artist' or 'Artist Dead Life'.<ref>Birth, Marriage, & Death, ''FamilySearch'' ([https://www.familysearch.org/search/record/results?count=20&query=%2Bgivenname%3Aemily~%20%2Bsurname%3Astannard~%20%2Bbirth_year%3A1802-1802~%20%2Bfather_givenname%3Adaniel~]).</ref>\n\nDuring her last years she lived at 12, Cathedral Street, Norwich, with her unmarried daughter Emily. She died there on 6 January 1885,<ref name=\"OBIT\">{{cite web |url= https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk|title= Norfolk Chronicle and Norwich Gazette \u2013 Saturday 17 January 1885|author=<!--Not stated--> |year= 2018|website= The British Newspaper Archive|publisher= [[British Library]]|access-date= 7 December 2018}}</ref> her will being proved by her daughter.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk/Calendar?surname=stannard&yearOfDeath=1885&page=3#calendar|title= Find a will|author=<!--Not stated--> |website= |publisher= Government of the United Kingdom|access-date= 7 December 2018}}</ref> Her obituary appeared in the local press the week following her death, mentioning that \"Mrs. Stannard had a great artistic merit, was a very clever painter of fruit, flowers, fish, game, and still life, and her pictures have always been highly esteemed by lovers of art\", and describing \"her kindly, gentle, modest, and simple nature (which) endeared her to all who had the pleasure of her acquaintance\".{{refn|1=Emily Stannard's full obituary in ''The Norfolk Chronicle'' read: \"We regret to announce the somewhat sudden death of a charming old lady, Mrs. Joseph Stannard, of 12, Cathedral-street, in this city, on Tuesday, the 6th inst. Mrs Joseph Stannard, n\u00e9e Coppin, was one of the last remaining links of the old Norwich School of Artists. She was the widow of the well-known and excellent artist, Joseph Stannard, who died in 1830, at the early age of 34 years, in the prime of life, and while rapidly and steadily advancing in power and fame. Mrs. Stannard had a great artistic merit, was a very clever painter of fruit, flowers, fish, game, and still life, and her pictures have always been highly esteemed by lovers of art. In 1820 she received the large gold medal from the Society of Arts for an original painting of flowers. In August of the same year she went with her father to Holland, where in the Hague Gallery she made truthful copies of two precious small fruit pictures. At Trippon House, Amsterdam, she obtained permission to reproduce the celebrated Flower Pictures by Van Huysum. Her copies were greatly praised by celebrated foreign connoisseurs of the day for their close similitude of the originals. At Amsterdam she complied with the conditions laid down by showing two specimens of her painting, the President of the Amsterdam Gallery, Mons. Apostal, expressing great satisfaction with her work, and she was allowed to make a copy of another Van Huysum. In 1821 she was presented with the large gold medal of the Society of Arts, London, for an original painting of fruit. In 1828, as Mrs. Joseph Stannard, she received the gold medal for an original painting of game. As late as 1870 she exhibited in an exhibition at Norwich two very pictures of flowers and song birds, elaborately and beautifully painted, both of them brilliant and effective, which were very highly spoken of in the local journals at the time. Her kindly, gentle, modest, and simple nature endeared her to all who had the pleasure of her acquaintance, by whom she will ever be remembered with great esteem, regard, and affection. Many of the last years of her life were smoothed and cheered by the loving care and companionship of an only daughter, to whom we tender our sincere sympathy\".<ref>{{cite news\n| date         = 17 January 1885\n| title        = The late Mrs. Joseph Stannard\n| url          = https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/search/results/1885-01-17?basicsearch=joseph%20stannard&exactsearch=false&county=norfolk%2c%20england&retrievecountrycounts=false&mostspecificlocation=norfolk%2c%20england&newspapertitle=norfolk%2bchronicle\n|url-access=subscription\n| work    = The Norfolk Chronicle\n| location     = Norwich\n| publisher = The British Newspaper Archive\n| access-date  = 5 April 2019\n}}</ref>|group=note}}\n\nHer gold medals were donated by her daughter to the new museum at [[Norwich Castle]] in 1894.{{sfn|Hill|2016}}{{refn|1=The museum described them as \"Three Gold Medals inscribed the \"Society of Arts and Commerce Promoted\" awarded to Mrs. Joseph Stannard for painting, and the Silver \"Honorary Pallet of the Society for Promoting Arts, Manufacturer and Commerce,\" awarded to Mrs. Coppin for Drawing\".<ref>Norwich Castle Museum Committee (1894), p. 15.</ref> Emily also donated the paintings of her parents and her grandmother Elizabeth Coppin, in what the author Kate Hill described as \"an unusual example of an attempt to memorialise women artists\".{{sfn|Hill|2016}}|group=note}} \n\nEmily Stannard continued to live at Cathedral Street until her death in 1894 at the age of 67.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk|title= Eastern Evening News|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 24 November 1894|website= British Newspaper Archive|access-date= 14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Background===\n{{further|Norwich School of painters}}\n\nThe Norwich School of painters was a unique phenomenon in the history of British 19th century art.{{sfn|Moore|1985|p=9}} [[Norwich]] was the first English city outside London where a school of artists arose.{{sfn|Cundall|1920|p=1}} It had more local-born artists than any subsequently-formed schools elsewhere,{{sfn|Hemingway|1979|pp=9, 79}} its most important artists being [[John Crome]], Emily Stannard's husband [[Joseph Stannard]], [[George Vincent (painter)|George Vincent]], [[Robert Ladbrooke]], [[James Stark (painter)|James Stark]], [[John Thirtle]] and [[John Sell Cotman]].{{sfn|Hemingway|1988|p=17}} The Norwich School artists were connected by geographical location, their depiction of Norwich and rural [[Norfolk]], and by close personal and professional relationships.{{refn|1=The Stannards were the most conspicuous family of still-life painters in nineteenth century England. [[Alfred Stannard]] and his older brother Joseph specialised in painting [[Landscape painting|landscapes]] and [[marine art]], but with the encouragement of Emily Stannard included still-life works in their repertoire. Her niece [[Eloise Harriet Stannard]] in turn became a prominent painter flowers and fruit.{{sfn|Nunn|1995|p=39}}|group=note}} By the end of the 19th century the paintings by the artists of the Norwich School, who had once been regarded as modern and progressive, were seen as belonging to a bygone age, a view that Professor [[Andrew Hemingway (art historian)|Andrew Hemingway]] has attributed to the \"mythology of rural Englishness\" that prevailed at the start of the 20th century.{{sfn|Hemingway|1988|p=30}}\n\nThe Norwich Society of Artists was founded in 1803.{{sfn|Rajnai|Stevens|1976|p=13}} It held annual exhibitions from 1805 to 1825 and again from 1828 until its dissolution in 1833.{{sfn|Rajnai|Stevens|1976|p=4}} Members of the Stannard family showed their pictures at the exhibitions, but they had few other artistic connections with their Norwich contemporaries. Emily Stannard, who became an honorary member of the Society in 1831, was the only member of the Stannard family to have a formal association with the Society.{{sfn|Moore|1985|p=95}}\n\n===Teaching===\n\nEmily, assisted by her daughter, had a career as an art teacher.{{sfn|Gray|2009|p=249}} Hardly any information about this aspect of her life is provided by her past or present biographers.\n\n===Works===\n[[File:Emily-Coppin-Stannard still-life-1824.jpg|thumb|''Floral still life with a silver-gilt cup'' (1824)]]\n[[File:Emily Coppin Stannard - Still Life with Mallard Snipes and Gold Medals.jpg|thumb|''Still Life with Mallard Snipes and Gold Medals'']]\n\nEmily Stannard and her niece [[Eloise Harriet Stannard]] are nowadays considered to be the finest British women still life painters of the nineteenth century.{{sfn|Walpole|1997|pp=58\u201359}} Stannard's early paintings were influenced by the Dutch masters Huysum and De Heem.{{Ambiguous|date=December 2018}}{{sfn|Moore|1985|p=104}} Both her depiction of vases and the finish of her depiction of flowers owed much to Huysum, and her unsigned works were sometimes attributed to 18th century Dutch painters.{{sfn|Mitchell|1973|pp=242\u20134}} ''Still life: Dead Ducks and a Hare with a Basket and Sprig of Holly'' reveals her debt to [[Jan Weenix]], whose work ''Dead Hare and Partidges'' she presumably saw when it was exhibited at the [[British Institution]]. Paintings by Dutch masters at [[English country house|country houses]] in Norfolk (such as at [[Wolterton Hall]]) may also have been available to her.{{sfn|Moore|1988|p=144}}\n\nShe first exhibited her works in 1816.{{sfn|Rajnai|Stevens|1976|p=87}} In 1821, aged seventeen, she was awarded the Norwich Society of Artists' gold medal for one of her flower paintings.{{sfn|Moore|1985|p=96}} She won a second medal the following year for a painting of a collection of fruit.{{sfn|Gray|2009|p=249}} She received a third gold medal in 1828 for a still life of game animals,{{sfn|Mackie|1901|p=354}} which was exhibited at the Norwich Society of Artists as ''Dead Game from Nature''.{{sfn|Rajnai|Stevens|1976|p=87}} Throughout her long career, which continued until shortly before her death at the age of 82, she continued to depict [[Flower bouquet|bouquets of flowers in vases]] and other traditional still life paintings of tableware, fruit or [[Game (hunting)|game animals]], set against monochrome backgrounds.{{sfn|Vincent|1992}}{{sfn|Walpole|1997|pp=58\u20139}}\n\nAlthough she usually exhibited her work in Norwich, she also exhibited paintings at the [[Royal Society of British Artists]] in 1824 and the [[British Institution]] from 1823 to 1825.{{sfn|Gray|2009|p=249}}\n\nAccording to the art historian and author Josephine Walpole, Emily Stannard's paintings display a \"natural talent\" and \"impeccable colour sense\".{{sfn|Walpole|1997|p=58}} According to Andrew Moore, her technique and command of composition strengthened in the years after her husband's death.{{sfn|Moore|1985|p=105}}\n\nOn least one occasion she signed a painting using her Christian name,{{sfn|Mitchell|1973|pp=242\u20134}} but her works are invariably signed 'Mrs. Joseph Stannard'. Her canvasses, which were often left unvarnished, were consistently painted with a thin, diluted paint, in a similar way to the works of the Dutch masters she studied.{{sfn|Moore|1988|p=144}}\n\nThe Norfolk Museums Collections is the only United Kingdom public art collection which possesses works by Emily Stannard. Her paintings there are: ''Still life: hamper with dead wood pigeon and leveret''; ''Still life: dead ducks and a hare with a basket and a sprig of holly'' (1853); ''Still life with dead game and a flagon and a string of onions'' (1847); ''Dead game and a gun'' (1835); ''Dead game'' (1837); ''Flowers''; ''Still life: group of dead game birds''; and ''Wild duck (study)''.{{sfn|Wright| Gordon|2006|p=743}}\n\nPrices paid for her paintings include \u00a3400 for ''Still life study of dead birds on a table oil on board'' in 2017, \u00a31600 for ''Still Life Study of Mixed Flowers and Fruit in Basket on Marble Ledge'' in 2015, \u00a3920 for ''Still Life Study of Mixed Flowers, Birds Nest and Butterfly on Marble Ledge'' in 2015, and \u00a3130 for a [[watercolour painting]] ''Tranquil River Landscape'' in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.keysauctions.co.uk/?s=emily+stannard&lots=1|title= Lot Results for: emily stannard|website= Keys Fine Art Auctioneers|accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref> Her larger painting ''The game larder'' (52 x 43.2&nbsp;cm) was sold at [[Christie's]] in 2013 for \u00a310,000.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.christies.com/lotfinder/Lot/emily-stannard-1803-1885-the-game-larder-5715041-details.aspx|title= Sale 1886 (Lot 483)|website= Christie's|accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist | refs=\n}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book | ref = harv |last= Cundall|first= Herbert Minton|date= 1920|title= The Norwich School|url= https://archive.org/details/cu31924014891992|location= London|publisher= Geoffrey Holme Ltd |page= |isbn= |author-link= }} {{free access}}\n*{{cite book |ref = harv |last=Dickes |first=William Frederick |date=1905 |title=The Norwich school of painting: being a full account of the Norwich exhibitions, the lives of the painters, the lists of their respecitve exhibits and descriptions of the pictures |url= https://archive.org/details/norwichschoolofp00dick/page/524|location= Norwich|publisher= Jarrold & Sons Ltd.|page= |isbn= |author-link= William Dickes}} {{free access}}\n*{{cite book |ref = harv |last= Gray|first= Sara|date= 2009|title= The Dictionary of British Women Artists|url=|location= Cambridge|publisher= Lutterworth Press|page= |isbn= |author-link= }}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Hemingway |first1=Andrew |authorlink1=Andrew Hemingway (art historian) |title=The Norwich School of Painters 1803-1833 |date=1979 |publisher=Phaidon |location=Oxford |isbn=9780714820019 |url=https://archive.org/details/norwichschoolofp00hemi }}\n*{{cite journal | ref = harv |last1= Hemingway|first1= Andrew |author-link1= Andrew Hemingway (art historian)|year= 1988|title= Cultural Philanthropy and the Invention of the Norwich School|journal= Oxford Art Journal|volume= 11|issue= 2|pages=17\u201339}}\n*{{cite book |ref = harv |last= Hill|first= Kate|date= 2016|title= Women and Museums 1850-1914: Modernity and the Gendering of Knowledge|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3o0LDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT89&lpg=PT89&dq=%22Emily+stannard%22+norwich&source=bl&ots=YRHn_xKSb4&sig=zu_hT0kDVdAW534zLIAMp8tx24A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiYvMW16tTeAhVrh4sKHabVCsg4FBDoATAAegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=%22Emily%20stannard%22%20norwich&f=false|location= Cambridge|publisher= Manchester University Press|page= |isbn= 978-0719081156|author-link= }}\n*{{cite book|ref= harv|last= Mackie|first= Charles|date= 1901|title= Norfolk Annals: A Chronological Record of Remarkable Events in the Nineteenth Century Vol. 2 (1851\u20131900)|url= https://archive.org/details/norwichschoolofp00hemi|